{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef7d71b0-80c6-4569-ab8c-ce363fb9f57a","content":"This is a great use case for **NuGet's Trusted Publishing** via OIDC — no API keys needed. Here's the two-part setup:\n\n## 1. NuGet.org Configuration\n\nOn [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org):\n1. Go to **Account** → **Trusted publishers**\n2. Add a publisher: set **Owner** = `myorg`, **Repo** = `mylib`, **Workflow** = `publish.yml`\n3. Optionally restrict to a GitHub Environment (e.g., `nuget-publish`)\n\n## 2. GitHub Actions Workflow\n\nI'll create the workflow file:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_01ERBorztutYMsyzcgEaM6JM","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating NuGet publish workflow"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_01CcXiTDPDwoZtF35ycuRoQd","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-c62fa6d02ff344d2aaad78fc4578cc18/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"2662c114-a881-4e2f-bc51-7baa687d43a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (no API keys). This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nNuGet.org now supports trusted publishing via OpenID Connect (OIDC), similar to PyPI. This lets you publish without storing API keys as secrets. Let me explain the setup.\n\nActually, let me think about what NuGet.org supports. As of my knowledge, NuGet.org added support for trusted publishers using OIDC tokens from GitHub Actions. Let me provide the accurate setup.\n\nThe key steps are:\n\n\n1. On NuGet.org: Go to your package management and add a trusted publisher by specifying your GitHub repository owner and repo name\n2. In your GitHub Actions workflow, use the OIDC token that GitHub automatically provides to authenticate with NuGet.org without needing an API key stored as a secret\n\nLet me clarify the exact mechanism here—NuGet.org's trusted publishing links a specific GitHub repository and workflow to your package, then your workflow requests an OIDC token and passes it to `dotnet nuget push` for authentication. I'm going to walk through the practical setup with actual workflow configuration and the nuget.org steps to make this concrete for them.","outputTokens":1120},"id":"c8b8c36f-78f8-43d3-b3a8-168b87d3d91b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:41:57.036Z","parentId":"5ab893c1-f22e-488a-b659-e708bb18de17"}
